Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Trim the root and the dark green leafy part from
the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways then thinly slice. Peel and grate the
@garlic{1%clove}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the
@green pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into small pieces. Finely
chop the @chives{1}(finely chopped).

> Tip: Use scissors to make this easier! Halve the chilli lengthways, deseed
> then finely chop.

Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then finely chop.

Heat a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat with a splash of @oil{}. Add the leek
and pepper. Stir and cook until soft, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> Tip: Don't worry if they colour slightly, this will just add to the flavour!

Meanwhile, drain and rinse the @red kidney beans{1} in a #sieve{}.

Once the veg are soft, add the @pork sausage meat{225%g}. Cook until browned,
~{5-6%minutes}, using a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Add the garlic, chilli (add as much or as little as you
like), @smoked paprika{1} and @ground cumin{1}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more. Pour
in the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1}, @water{100%ml} and
kidney beans. Stir in the @red wine stock paste{28%g} to dissolve. Simmer until
thick, ~{10-12%minutes}.

While the chilli cooks, make the tortilla chips! Using some #scissors{}, cut
each @super soft tortillas with whole wheat{2} into eight triangles (we used
one tortilla per person but if you want to use two per person, that's fine -
you have enough!).

Place the chips on a #baking tray{} in a single layer and drizzle over some
@oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Bake on the top shelf of your
oven until golden, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> Tip: Keep an eye on them to make sure they don't burn!

Taste the chilli and add more salt and pepper if necessary. Serve the sausage
chilli in #bowls{} with a spoonful of @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g} on top and
a sprinkling of chives. Place the tortilla chips on the side of the bowl
(for scooping purposes). Enjoy!